content.description:
When a re-render is necessary (adding/removing attachments, content changes), the DOM is rebuilt from scratch. This destroys scroll positions, focus state, and other transient DOM state. The Scroll State Preservation pattern saves and restores this state across re-renders.

## The Problem

A re-render replaces DOM nodes:

```javascript
mainView.innerHTML = '';
mainView.appendChild(await renderItem(itemId));
```

Everything the user was looking at â€” scroll position within windows, which element had focus, text selections â€” is lost.

## The Solution: Save Before, Restore After

### 1. Save scroll positions keyed by item ID

```javascript
const scrollStates = new Map();
const windows = mainView.querySelectorAll('[data-item-id]');
windows.forEach(wrapper => {
  const itemId = wrapper.getAttribute('data-item-id');
  const content = wrapper.querySelector('.window-content');
  if (content) {
    scrollStates.set(itemId, {
      scrollTop: content.scrollTop,
      scrollLeft: content.scrollLeft
    });
  }
});
```

### 2. Re-render the DOM

```javascript
const domNode = await this.renderItem(itemId);
mainView.innerHTML = '';
mainView.appendChild(domNode);
```

### 3. Restore scroll positions after render

```javascript
setTimeout(() => {
  const newWindows = mainView.querySelectorAll('[data-item-id]');
  newWindows.forEach(wrapper => {
    const itemId = wrapper.getAttribute('data-item-id');
    const saved = scrollStates.get(itemId);
    if (saved) {
      const content = wrapper.querySelector('.window-content');
      if (content) {
        content.scrollTop = saved.scrollTop;
        content.scrollLeft = saved.scrollLeft;
      }
    }
  });
}, 0);
```

## Key Implementation Details

- **Use `data-item-id`** for stable tracking â€” not DOM position or array index
- **Use `.window-content`** class for consistent element selection
- **`setTimeout(..., 0)`** ensures DOM is fully rendered before restoration
- **Map keyed by item ID** handles reordering gracefully

## Extended State

The same pattern applies to other transient DOM state:

| State | Save | Restore |
|-------|------|---------|
| Scroll position | `scrollTop`, `scrollLeft` | Set properties |
| Focus | `document.activeElement` | `.focus()` |
| Text selection | `getSelection().getRangeAt(0)` | `setBaseAndExtent()` |
| Textarea cursor | `selectionStart`, `selectionEnd` | Set properties |

## When to Use

This pattern is needed whenever `api.update()` triggers a re-render that replaces DOM nodes the user is interacting with. It's most commonly used in:

- Container views (spatial canvas) when adding/removing children
- The viewport when the root item changes
- Any view that does full DOM replacement on update

## Hob Views: Avoiding the Problem

In Hob views, the best approach is often to avoid full re-renders that destroy scroll positions in the first place:

- **Selector-filtered reactivity**: `(get-item id :select fn)` skips re-renders when the selected data hasn't changed. The spatial-canvas Hob view uses this so drag/resize/z-index changes don't trigger re-renders at all.
- **Stable skeleton pattern**: Build the DOM once with `hiccup->dom+`, then update specific containers via `dom-set-content!`. Sibling containers (and their scroll positions) are untouched.

When a Hob view does re-render (structural changes like add/remove child), the save-before-render/restore-after pattern still applies. The spatial-canvas Hob view implements this by saving scroll states into a plain JS object before building the new DOM, then restoring via `requestAnimationFrame` after render.

## See Also

- [Silent Update Pattern](item://c0c0c0c0-0010-0000-0000-000000000000) â€” Avoiding re-renders entirely
- [Stable Skeleton with Surgical Updates](item://c0c0c0c0-0017-0000-0000-000000000000) â€” Build once, update surgically
- [Spatial Windowing](item://ef793c27-2d4b-4c99-b05a-2769db5bc5a9) â€” Primary consumer of these patterns
